<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_hub_flow` row that
    declares the `x_casemgmt_validate_open_transition` Flow Designer
    SUBFLOW (type=subflow) inside the scoped application `x_casemgmt`
    (Case Management).

    PURPOSE (AAP Section 0.5.5 verbatim transition row):
        From    To    Required condition         Failure handling
        Draft   Open  assigned_group populated   Surface form-level error

    This subflow is one of FIVE shared transition-validation subflows under
    `servicenow-case-management-poc/flows/sub_flows/`. It is called by both
    parent state-machine flows whenever a case's `status` field changes
    to `Open`:

      - ../general_inquiry_state_machine.xml
            (when a General Inquiry case enters the Open state from Draft)
      - ../complaint_state_machine.xml
            (when a Complaint case enters the Open state from Draft)

    Per AAP Section 0.5.5, the Draft -> Open transition has exactly one
    precondition: assigned_group must be populated. There is no role gate,
    no membership check, and no side effect on success - unlike
    validate_pending_transition (sets pending_reason) or
    validate_closed_transition (sets closed_date and gates on the
    x_casemgmt_case_manager role), the Open transition only validates that
    the case has been routed to a queue (the assigned_group) before it
    leaves the Draft sub-state. This is the simplest precondition gate
    in the state-machine - one field check, one error path.

    SEMANTIC SOURCE-SIDE REFERENCE (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported):

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/
        java/com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/pipeline/presave/
        CaseFileQueueHandler.java line 49-59 - the canonical ArkCase
        analog of this subflow. CaseFileQueueHandler.execute(...)
        was a pre-save pipeline handler that:

            1) Read the queue name from the pipeline context
                   String queueName = pipelineContext.getEnqueueName();
            2) Resolved the AcmQueue entity by that name
                   AcmQueue queue = getAcmQueueDao().findByName(queueName);
            3) Set the queue on the case file entity
                   entity.setQueue(queue);
            4) Forced the case status to ACTIVE
                   entity.setStatus("ACTIVE");

        That single Java handler conflated TWO responsibilities:
        (a) routing the case to a queue (ArkCase's organizational
        equivalent of an assigned group) and (b) forcing the status
        to ACTIVE. The ServiceNow target SEPARATES these concerns:

            - The assigned_group (queue-equivalent) is set by the
              caller (an internal user via the form, an external
              requester via the portal which submits with status=Draft
              and assigned_group=null, or a flow / Business Rule).
            - The status transition Draft -> Open is REQUESTED by the
              caller (e.g., the form's Save action with the new status
              value).
            - This subflow GATES the transition: if the caller has
              not also populated assigned_group, the transition is
              rejected with a blocking error and the saved case row
              remains at status=Draft.

        The semantic equivalence is preserved: ArkCase's "queue must
        be assigned before the case becomes ACTIVE" is now ServiceNow's
        "assigned_group must be populated before status becomes Open."
        The mechanism (Java pre-save pipeline -> Flow Designer subflow)
        differs; the rule is identical.

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/
        java/com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/service/
        ChangeCaseFileStateService.java line 79-114 - the central
        ArkCase case state-machine service. Its changeCaseState(auth,
        caseId, newState, ipAddress) method:

            1) Loaded the CaseFile by ID
            2) Returned early if status unchanged
            3) Set the new status on the entity (line 95)
            4) For "CLOSED" status, set the close timestamp (97-100)
            5) Saved the entity (102)
            6) Raised an event for downstream notification listeners
               (106 - intentionally NOT replicated in the ServiceNow
               target because email is disabled per AAP Section 0.7.2)

        That single method handled EVERY transition by string-matching
        the `newState` parameter; the ServiceNow target instead splits
        per-transition logic into FIVE dedicated subflows (this one,
        plus validate_inprogress, validate_pending, validate_resolved,
        validate_closed). The gating intent ("require precondition X
        before allowing transition to status Y") is preserved; the
        layer at which it is enforced (Java service vs. Flow Designer
        subflow) differs.

    WHAT THIS SUBFLOW DOES:

        1. Receives a single Reference input `case_record` (the
           x_casemgmt_case GlideRecord whose status is being changed
           to Open). The parent flow passes $trigger.current.
        2. Calls x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator.canTransitionToOpen(
           case_record) via an embedded script step. The Script Include
           reads case_record.getValue('assigned_group') and returns:
             - { ok: true } when assigned_group is non-empty
             - { ok: false, error: 'Required field assigned_group is empty.' }
               when assigned_group is null/empty/whitespace
             - { ok: false, error: 'Case record is missing.' } when
               case_record itself is null/undefined (defensive guard
               that should not occur in normal parent-flow invocation
               but exists to fail-fast if a future caller passes a
               missing record).
        3. Inspects the validator's `ok` output. If false, executes a
           Throw Error step whose message is bound to the validator's
           `error` output. Flow Designer's Throw Error implicitly
           invokes gs.addErrorMessage(message) and setAbortAction(true)
           on the triggering GlideRecord transaction, so the error
           appears on the form and the status update is rolled back.
        4. If `ok` is true, the subflow returns successfully. There is
           NO side effect on success - no field is auto-set, no event
           is queued, no notification is sent. The parent flow simply
           proceeds and the status update is persisted.

    CRITICAL DIFFERENCES FROM SIBLING SUBFLOWS:

      - vs validate_inprogress_transition.xml: That subflow validates
        BOTH assigned_agent populated AND group-membership. This
        subflow validates ONLY assigned_group populated. The
        membership check would be redundant on the Draft -> Open
        edge because assigned_agent is OPTIONAL on Open (per AAP
        Section 0.5.7 the agent is "Optional; must be member of
        assigned_group" - meaning assignment can happen later when
        the case transitions to In Progress).

      - vs validate_pending_transition.xml: That subflow has NO
        precondition gate (always permitted from In Progress) but
        DOES set the pending_reason side effect. This subflow has
        a precondition gate (assigned_group populated) but NO
        side effect.

      - vs validate_resolved_transition.xml: That subflow gates on
        a CHILD-record-aggregate condition (all child case_task rows
        must have status=Closed) and uses the verbatim AAP error
        message "All tasks must be closed before resolving this case."
        This subflow gates on a SINGLE-FIELD condition on the case
        row itself and uses the non-verbatim default error
        "Required field assigned_group is empty." (the AAP Section
        0.7.4 only specifies verbatim messages for the Resolved /
        terminal-Closed / backward-Draft transitions; the Open
        transition is "Surface form-level error" without a verbatim
        message).

      - vs validate_closed_transition.xml: That subflow gates on a
        ROLE-membership condition (caller has x_casemgmt_case_manager
        role) AND sets a closed_date side effect. This subflow has
        no role gate and no side effect.

    DELEGATE-TO-SCRIPT-INCLUDE PATTERN (assigned-folder rule 8):

        The actual validation logic - "is assigned_group populated?"
        - lives in
        ../../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml
        method canTransitionToOpen(caseGr). This subflow is a thin
        orchestration shell that:

          - Standardizes the calling pattern across all five
            transition-validation subflows
          - Surfaces the validator's error message verbatim via
            Throw Error
          - Aborts the parent flow's transaction on validation failure

        The validator can also be called directly from a Business Rule
        (synchronous, before-update) for defense-in-depth; today only
        the subflow path exercises canTransitionToOpen. The validator's
        return shape { ok: boolean, error?: string } is uniform across
        all transition guards (canTransitionToOpen,
        canTransitionToInProgress, canTransitionToResolved,
        canTransitionToClosed, validateNoBacktransition) so the same
        subflow scaffolding (script step -> if -> throw error) works
        for every gate.

    DEFENSE-IN-DEPTH (assigned-folder rule 11):

        - The companion business rule
          ../../business_rules/x_casemgmt_block_draft_backtransition.xml
          handles the OPPOSITE direction (Any -> Draft is PROHIBITED)
          with the AAP Section 0.7.4 verbatim error message
          "Cases cannot be returned to Draft."
        - This subflow handles only the FORWARD Draft -> Open
          transition.
        - Together with validate_inprogress_transition,
          validate_pending_transition, validate_resolved_transition,
          validate_closed_transition, and the block_draft_backtransition
          and block_terminal_closed business rules, every cell in the
          AAP Section 0.5.5 transition matrix is enforced.

    TYPE / SUBFLOW SEMANTICS (assigned-folder rule 4):

        - <type>subflow</type> - this record IS a subflow, not a flow
          and not an action. A subflow is server-side, called by other
          flows (or invoked directly via the Script API
          new sn_fd.FlowAPI().executeSubflow(...)) and runs to
          completion synchronously within the caller's transaction.
        - <sc_callable>false</sc_callable> - the subflow is NOT
          callable from a service catalog item. It is invoked
          internally by parent state-machine flows.
        - <callable_by_client_api>false</callable_by_client_api> - the
          subflow is NOT exposed to client-side scripts. It runs
          server-side only. Per AAP Section 0.7.2, no global writes
          are permitted; restricting to server-side ensures the
          validator and the case GlideRecord are only manipulated by
          server-trusted code paths.

    RUN-AS / EXECUTION CONTEXT (assigned-folder rule 5):

        - <run_as>caller</run_as> - the subflow inherits the run-as
          context of the calling parent flow. The parent state-machine
          flows run as system_user (per their own definitions) so
          validation occurs with full privilege; ACL gating against
          the user who triggered the case update is enforced
          separately at the case row's table-level ACL layer
          (see ../../acl/x_casemgmt_case_*.xml).

