        - <sys_scope> resolves the scope record BY NAME (x_casemgmt)
        - <sys_package> resolves the application record BY NAME
          (x_casemgmt)
        - The snapshot JSON's "reference_table" field uses the table
          NAME ("x_casemgmt_case"), not its sys_id.
        - The snapshot JSON's "script_includes_used" array uses the
          API NAME ("x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator"), not its
          sys_id.
        - The script body inside the snapshot's "script" field
          instantiates the validator via its scope-qualified API name:
          new x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator(). The platform's
          script engine resolves this BY NAME, not by sys_id.
        - The <sys_id> element below is THIS record's own deterministic
          primary key (MD5 of "x_casemgmt_validate_open_transition" =
          968df74ca78c07ed1dd3ea6c755963d0), which is permitted because
          the AAP "no hardcoded sys_id" rule applies to REFERENCE
          fields targeting OTHER rows. This record's own sys_id is
          its primary key, not a reference. Deriving it from the
          stable name guarantees idempotent re-import on a fresh PDI:
          re-importing the same Update Set produces the same sys_id,
          which collides on the existing record and updates it in
          place rather than creating a duplicate. This is the same
          convention used by every other deterministically-keyed
